5d6.title: Introduction to Logical Decision Theory for Computer Scientists
5d6.clickbait: 'Logical decision theory' from a math/programming standpoint, including how two agents with mutual knowledge of each other's code can cooperate on the Prisoner's Dilemma.
5d6.text:
# Introduction: The Prisoner's Dilemma

In the classic presentation of the [prisoners_dilemma Prisoner's Dilemma], you and your fellow bank robber have been arrested and imprisoned.  You cannot communicate with each other.  You are facing a prison sentence of one year each.  Both of you have been offered a chance to betray the other (Defect); someone who Defects gets one year off their own prison sentence, but adds two years onto the other person's prison sentence.

So if $(o_1, o_2)$ is the outcome for Player 1 and Player 2 respectively, the outcome matrix for the classical Prisoner's Dilemma is:

$$\begin{tabular}{r|c|c}
& Player 2 defects: & Player 2 cooperates: \\
Player 1 defects: & (2 years, 2 years) & (0 years, 3 years) \\
Player 1 cooperates: & (3 years, 0 years) & (1 year, 1 year)
\end{tabular}$$

Each year in prison corresponds to negative utility.  If we want to rewrite this as a purer game with moves D and C and positive payoffs where \$X denotes "X utility", we could more simply write the game as:

$$\begin{tabular}{r|c|c}
& P2: D: & P2: C: \\
P1: D: & (\$1, \$1) & (\$0, \$3) \\
P1: C: & (\$3, \$0) & (\$2, \$2)
\end{tabular}$$

On currently standard decision theory, it is said to be 'rational' (yes, we'll go into the fight over this term shortly) for a selfish player to play Defect in the Prisoner's Dilemma.  This is bothersome because if both players play Defect, it leads to the outcome (\$1, \$1) which is [pareto_dominated Pareto dominated] by the outcome (\$2, \$2) which both players would prefer.  It seems like there in some sense a way to do better, which, on the standard theory, *two* rational agents somehow cannot manage to grasp for themselves.

There have been many objections to the setup that yields this bothersome conclusion.  For example:  "In the real world, you would have some fellow-feeling for your fellow conspirator, and negatively value their prison sentence; real people aren't entirely selfish."  Or, "Defecting in the Prisoner's Dilemma would ruin your reputation and maybe lead to reprisals after you got out of prison."  We can try to construct a [true_prisoners_dilemma True Prisoner's Dilemma] by modifying the circumstances so as to yield an outcome matrix whose utilities really are in the proportion of the original Prisoner's Dilemma: for example, two charities which each firmly believe in their mission, know some detrimental facts about the other charity, and which are both in private, secret meetings with a philanthropist deciding how to divide funding between them.

Even accepting the basic setup and its outcome matrix, a number of philosophers and computer scientists have had trouble swallowing the conclusion that two rational selfish agents must mutually defect in the Prisoner's Dilemma.  [DouglasHofstadter Douglas Hofstadter] suggested that 'superrationality' would include taking into account that the other agent was reasoning in a situation very similar to yours, and that the two of you were likely to arrive at similar answers, whatever that answer was.

In the Iterated Prisoner's Dilemma - like playing the Prisoner's Dilemma against the same player 100 times in a row - a famous strategy, Tit for Tat, just does whatever the opponent did on the last round.  This strategy usually does extremely well in tournaments, including against much more complicated entries.

But suppose we have two 'rational' agents (that is, rational accordingly currently standard decision theory) playing the Prisoner's Dilemma with a known horizon - that is, both agents know the game stops after the 100th round.  Then on the 100th round, both agents will Defect, since this move has no future consequences.  On the 99th round, both agents, knowing the other will Defect regardless on the 100th round, will also Defect.  And so on, until by induction we have proven that both agents Defect against each other on the 1st round.

Many people have found this an unsatisfactory state of affairs.  But for several decades, it had proven hard to articulate some simple, general, formal decision theory - some alternative formal notion of 'rationality' - which would make it possible for rational agents *not* to defect against each other on the first round of the Iterated Prisoner's Dilemma.

## Prisoner's Dilemma with common knowledge of code

Imagine a Prisoner's Dilemma tournament - actually, we ran a tournament almost exactly like this, so it's not just imagination - in which submitted bots compete against each other in the *one-shot* Prisoner's Dilemma, but with *knowledge of the other bot's code.*  This is the "program equilibrium" problem posed by Tennenholtz in 2010.  [todo: add cite]

At minimum (as Tennenholtz observed) you can do better in this tournament than by defecting all the time, if you notice when the other bot's code is an exact copy of your own code, and if so, cooperate.  But is it possible to do even better?

Well, suppose you find yourself facing a bot like this:

    def FairBot1(otherAgent):
       if (otherAgent(FairBot1) == Cooperate):
         return Cooperate
       else:
         return Defect

If you were a bot facing FairBot1 (or if you prefer, imagine that a reasonably smart machine intelligence is facing FairBot1) then it would seem clear that the smart decision is to Cooperate with FairBot1.

As it happens, this reply to FairBot1 has already taken us beyond the advice of *causal decision theory,* this being the currently standard version of decision theory.  Causal decision theory says "Choose according to the causal consequences of your physical action," and as causal decision theory defines all that, your cooperation in the Prisoner's Dilemma is not said to *cause* FairBot1 to cooperate.  (If this sounds odd, see later sections for an explanation of causal decision theory.)

FairBot1 itself, despite the resemblance to Tit for Tat, is definitely not an optimal player in the Prisoner's Dilemma tournament we just defined.  One reason is that FairBot1 cooperates with CooperateBot.

    def CooperateBot(otherAgent):
      return Cooperate

One also observes that when FairBot1 plays against a copy of itself, it goes into an infinite loop and never returns a value.  (Though in one definition of the tournament, if you run out of time, this automatically returns Cooperate; so maybe in that sense FairBot1 could be said to Cooperate with itself.  But this is still not optimal intelligent reasoning.)

By the end of this introduction, we'll have seen a program which:

- Cooperates with FairBot1 (and an improved variant FairBot2 which doesn't run out of time when playing itself!)
- Cooperates with itself.
- Defects against CooperateBot
- Is provably never exploited (it never plays Cooperate when the other player plays Defect).

...and we'll also have shown that this program is a special case of something that looks like a more general, unified decision-making program.

Hopefully all of this sounds neat; but does it have any larger implications?

## LDT and its general implications

You may have heard it asserted that it is not 'rational' to vote in elections, since your own vote has a very tiny probability of changing the outcome.

When people talk about 'rationality' in this sense, they're actually appealing to causal decision theory (which is, again, the standard).  CDT says that the principle of rational choice is to decide according to the causal consequences of our own physical act (in a certain formal sense we'll get into shortly).  Unless your voting *causes* many other people to vote, as opposed to all of you just being in *similar situations,* CDT says that the expected utility of voting versus not-voting just comes from comparing the world where you voted, versus the world where everything else was the same except you didn't vote.

So if an election of a million voters was settled by exactly two votes, then, says CDT, nobody's act changed the outcome.  But if the election was settled by exactly one vote, then, says CDT, *everyone* who voted for the winning party was responsible for the whole election.

The new family of decision theories shortly to be presented, *logical decision theories,* embody what is argued to be a better candidate for the principle of rational choice:  We should decide as if deciding the *logical output* of our *decision algorithm.*

In a lot of everyday cases, (variants of) LDT will give us the same result as classical CDT.  Knowing LDT doesn't automatically mean you can end up mutually cooperating in the Prisoner's Dilemma; in real life you may not know enough about the other person's algorithm to execute the kind of 'logical handshake' where you each simulate the other cooperating only if you cooperate.  

Elections are one of the cases where LDT makes a big difference in what we think is rational or normative, compared to classical CDT.  Populations voting in elections are large enough that there may reasonably be many other people with decision algorithms similar to yours - not everyone, but a logically correlated cohort large enough that it might matter in close elections.  You can reasonably believe that everyone in your cohort will probably decide to vote (or not vote) in something like logically correlated unison, and ask whether the probable benefit is worth the cost to all of you.

LDT might also be important in cases where a small probability of logical correlation still matters a lot.  For example, the 100-round Iterated Prisoner's Dilemma, where even a small probability of being able to execute cooperation is reason enough to try cooperating on round one.

LDT also matters in cases where we can deliberately broadcast our decision algorithm, for instance by acquiring a reputation for acting according to LDT.  [todo: Ultimatum Game example here]

[todo: brief discussion of reflective stability and basis for sufficiently advanced AI algorithms.]

[todo: but maybe the most immediate consequence for most comp-sci readers is that we can now stop going around saying that rational agents don't vote in elections and defect against each other in the Prisoner's Dilemma, which may have had some negative effects on morale.]

5n9.title: Causal decision theories
5n9.clickbait: On CDT, to choose rationally, you should imagine the world where your physical act changes, then imagine running that world forward in time.  (Therefore, it's irrational to vote in elections.)

5pt.title: Newcomblike decision problems
5pt.clickbait: Decision problems in which your choice correlates with something other than its physical consequences (say, because somebody has predicted you very well) can do weird things to some decision theories.

5pv.title: Newcomb's Problem
5pv.clickbait: There are two boxes in front of you, Box A and Box B.  You can take both boxes, or only Box B.  Box A contains $1000.  Box B contains $1,000,000 if and only if Omega predicted you'd take only Box B.

5px.title: Evidential decision theories
5px.clickbait: Theories which hold that the principle of rational choice is "Choose the act that would be the best news, if somebody told you that you'd chosen that act."

5py.title: Prisoner's Dilemma
5py.clickbait: You and an accomplice have been arrested.  Both of you must decide, in isolation, whether to testify against the other prisoner--which subtracts one year from your sentence, and adds two to theirs.

5pz.title: True Prisoner's Dilemma
5pz.clickbait: A scenario that would reproduce the ideal payoff matrix of the Prisoner's Dilemma about human beings who care about their public reputation and each other.

5qn.title: Death in Damascus
5qn.clickbait: Death tells you that It is coming for you tomorrow.  You can stay in Damascus or flee to Aleppo.  Whichever decision you actually make is the wrong one.  This gives some decision theories trouble.

5s0.title: Parfit's Hitchhiker
5s0.clickbait: You are dying in the desert.  A truck-driver who is very good at reading faces finds you, and offers to drive you into the city if you promise to pay $1,000 on arrival.  You are a selfish rationalist.

5tp.title: Ultimatum Game
5tp.clickbait: A Proposer decides how to split $10 between themselves and the Responder.  The Responder can take what is offered, or refuse, in which case both parties get nothing.

7ry.title: Coherence theorems
7ry.clickbait: A 'coherence theorem' shows that something bad happens to an agent if its decisions can't be viewed as 'coherent' in some sense. E.g., an inconsistent preference ordering leads to going in circles.
